      <h2>Dark Skies — Bortle Class 3</h2>
      <p>Goswick Ranch sits under <strong>Bortle Class 3</strong> skies — a level of darkness rarely available within two hours of a major metropolitan area. On clear nights, the Milky Way is a brilliant structural band with distinct lanes and clouds of nebulosity visible to the naked eye. The Gegenschein (a faint oval glow opposite the Sun) and the entire zodiacal band are routinely visible.</p>
      <p>Peak viewing season runs from <strong>October through June</strong>. The monsoon season (July–September) brings cloud cover that reduces transparency. The nearest significant light pollution source is Prescott, 27 miles to the west — its glow is largely blocked by the Bradshaw ridgeline.</p>

      <h2>Wildlife</h2>
      <p>The Madrean chaparral and lower ponderosa zone surrounding Goswick Ranch supports a diverse mix of wildlife. Key species:</p>

      <h3>Mammals</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mule deer</strong> — Commonly seen at dawn and dusk. Bucks are visible in autumn during the rut (November–December).</li>
        <li><strong>Mountain lions</strong> — Present throughout the Bradshaws. Rarely encountered directly; protect small pets and livestock outdoors at night.</li>
        <li><strong>Wild turkeys</strong> — Common at middle elevations year-round.</li>
        <li><strong>Black bears</strong> — Uncommon; present in upper Bradshaws in late summer. Secure trash and outdoor food.</li>
        <li><strong>Javelina (collared peccary)</strong> — Common at lower elevations near cactus.</li>
        <li><strong>Coatimundi</strong> — Occasional summer visitors from the south; travel in groups.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Reptiles</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Black-tailed rattlesnake</strong> and <strong>Arizona black rattlesnake</strong> — Both documented up to 6,000 feet. Watch where you step from April through October.</li>
        <li><strong>Gila monster</strong> — Rare above 5,000 feet; legally protected — do not disturb.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Birds</h3>
      <p>Year-round residents include zone-tailed hawks, Mexican jays, acorn woodpeckers, Steller's jays, and white-breasted nuthatches. Summer brings western tanagers, Scott's orioles, and multiple hummingbird species. Migrant species pass through in spring and fall.</p>

      <h2>Hiking &amp; Outdoor Recreation</h2>
      <p><strong>Prescott National Forest</strong> encompasses the Bradshaw Mountains with 450+ miles of trails for hiking, mountain biking, and horseback riding. No permits required for day use.</p>

      <h3>Seasonal Highlights</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Spring (April–May):</strong> Wildflower season — penstemon, lupine, globe mallow in bloom</li>
        <li><strong>Summer (June–Sept):</strong> Morning hikes before monsoon storms; dramatic cloud formations</li>
        <li><strong>Fall (October–November):</strong> Senator Highway fall color drive — peak in mid-to-late October</li>
        <li><strong>Winter (December–March):</strong> Snow at upper elevations; best stargazing conditions</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Equestrian Recreation</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Groom Creek Horse Camp</strong> — Prescott National Forest equestrian campground; corrals, water, and forest trails</li>
        <li><strong>Lynx Lake Recreation Area</strong> — Equestrian-friendly trails; note boat launch closed in late 2024 for repairs (verify current status)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>For equestrian services, see <a href={`${base}/resources/services/`}>Local Services</a> for Los Caballos mobile equine vet, Olsen's Grain, and Prescott Livestock Auction.</p>

      <h2>Agua Fria National Monument</h2>
      <p>~20–30 miles south via I-17 and Bloody Basin Road. BLM-managed; 71,000 acres of high desert plateau with prehistoric pueblo sites, thousands of petroglyphs, dispersed free camping, and excellent birding. No entrance fees.</p>

      <h2>Arcosanti</h2>
      <p>~11–15 miles via I-17 and Cordes Junction. Paolo Soleri's visionary experimental city — a living laboratory for "arcology." Guided tours Thursday through Monday. Source of the famous Cosanti wind bells.</p>

      <h2>Jerome National Historic Landmark</h2>
      <p>~40 miles northeast via AZ-69 and US-89A. Former copper-mining boom town, now a vibrant arts and wine destination on the side of Mingus Mountain at 5,200 feet.</p>

      <h2>Verde Valley Wine Trail</h2>
      <p>Designated AVA in 2021. ~35–50 miles via AZ-69. 15+ tasting rooms in Jerome and Cottonwood. Notable wineries: Page Springs Cellars, Caduceus Cellars/Merkin Vineyards, Alcantara Vineyards, Javelina Leap Vineyard.</p>

      <h2>Prescott</h2>
      <p>27 miles northwest (~40 min). Arizona's "mile-high city" at 5,368 feet. Walkable historic downtown, Whiskey Row, Sharlot Hall Museum, Phippen Museum of Western Art, World's Oldest Rodeo (held annually since 1888), and free summer concerts on Courthouse Plaza.</p>
      <p><strong>Prescott Airport (PRC)</strong> — 27–28 miles from Goswick Ranch. United Express (SkyWest) service to LAX and DEN. Free long-term parking.</p>

      <h2>Sedona</h2>
      <p>~60 miles northeast (~65 min via AZ-69 and AZ-89A). Red rock scenery, hiking, spas, and galleries. Best visited on weekdays. Oak Creek Canyon is spectacular in late October.</p>

